text="Categorical structure in theory of arithmetic">Categorical structure in theory of arithmetic</fr:title><fr:taxon>Reference</fr:taxon><fr:meta
name="doi">10.48550/arXiv.2304.05477</fr:meta><fr:meta
name="bibtex"><![CDATA[@misc{lingyuanye-2023-arithmetic,
  title={Categorical Structure in Theory of Arithmetic},
  author={Lingyuan Ye},
  year={2023},
  eprint={2304.05477},
  archivePrefix={arXiv},
  primaryClass={math.LO}
}]]></fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>In this paper, we provide a categorical analysis of the arithmetic theory <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\Sigma _1]]></fr:tex>. We will provide a categorical proof of the classical result that the provably total recursive functions in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\Sigma _1]]></fr:tex> are exactly the primitive recursive functions. Our strategy is to first construct a coherent theory of arithmetic <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {T}]]></fr:tex>, and prove that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {T}]]></fr:tex> presents the initial coherent category equipped with a parameterized natural number object. This allows us to derive the provably recursive total functions in <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {T}]]></fr:tex> are exactly the primitive recursive ones, and establish some other constructive properties about <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {T}]]></fr:tex>. We also sho that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathbb {T}]]></fr:tex> is exactly the <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\Pi _2]]></fr:tex>-fragment of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\Sigma _1]]></fr:tex>, and conclude that they have the same class of provably total recursive functions.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
